e state of the working class (winning a Pulitzer Prize in the process). In Someplace Like America, they follow the lives of several families over the thirty-year span to present an intimate and devastating portrait of workers going jobless. This brilliant and essential study—begun in the trickle-down Reagan years and culminating with the recent banking catastrophe—puts a human face on today’s grim economic numbers. It also illuminates the courage and resolve with which the next generation faces the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPovertyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUnemployedzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aWorking classzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aWorking poorzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abiographical.  ablue collar.  acareer.  acurrent events.  adevastating portrait.  aeconomic numbers.  aeconomics.  aengaging.  afamily.  ahistory.  ajournalism.  alabor industrial relations.  alabor relations.  amiddle class.  amoney and power.  amoney.  aphotobook.  aphotography.  apolitical science.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apoverty and inequality.  apoverty.  asocial history.  asocial issues.  asocial justice.  asocial science.  asociology.  astunning photographs.  athoughtful analysis.  aunemployment.  aurban decay.  avivid stories.  aworking class america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027451840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095650640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956506/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d20